TITLE: Reverting Accidental Submodule Changes in Git
DESCRIPTION: A sequence of commands to fix accidentally committed changes to a submodule (like `src/tools/cargo`). It involves finding the offending commit, checking out the correct version of the submodule from the previous commit, creating a fixup commit, and then autosquashing during an interactive rebase.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/master/src/doc/rustc-dev-guide/src/git.md#_snippet_8

LANGUAGE: sh
CODE:
```
# 1. Find the commit
git log --stat -n1 src/tools/cargo

# 2. Revert the submodule change for that commit
# Replace <my-commit> with the hash from step 1
git checkout <my-commit>~ src/tools/cargo

# 3. Create a fixup commit
git commit --fixup <my-commit>

# 4. Repeat for other affected commits/submodules

# 5. Squash the fixup commits
git rebase --autosquash -i upstream/master

# 6. Push the corrected history
git push --force-with-lease
```

